<div class="container">
    <h1>The Browser</h1>
    <p>A <strong>web browser</strong> is the application that allows users to access and interact with websites. It works as a <em>client</em> in the client-server model, sending requests to servers and displaying the responses as web pages.</p>

    <h2>Main Responsibilities</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Sending Requests:</strong> The browser sends HTTP or HTTPS requests to web servers when you type a URL or click a link.</li>
        <li><strong>Rendering Content:</strong> It takes the response (HTML, CSS, JavaScript, images, etc.) and renders it visually for the user.</li>
        <li><strong>Executing Scripts:</strong> The browser runs JavaScript code to make pages dynamic and interactive.</li>
        <li><strong>Managing Storage:</strong> It stores cookies, local storage, and session data to maintain user state.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example</h2>
    <p>If you type <code>www.example.com</code> in the address bar:</p>
    <ol>
        <li>The browser sends a request to the server hosting <code>example.com</code>.</li>
        <li>The server responds with an HTML page and related files.</li>
        <li>The browser downloads these resources and renders the page for the user.</li>
    </ol>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Simplified Request Example</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-http">
GET /index.html HTTP/1.1
Host: www.example.com
User-Agent: Chrome/Edge/Firefox
Accept: text/html
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>In this example, the browser sends a <code>GET</code> request for the <code>index.html</code> page. The server then responds with the HTML file that the browser displays.</p>

